By default, we set the fraction of malicious clients to 20% following the default setting in [9]. Table I shows that, on Fashion-MNIST dataset, Multi-Krum and Bulyan algorithms perform robustness under LF attack, but they fail in the other attacks.
FLTrust is relatively good that in a few experiments it achieves the same performance as ours in the non-IID case, while under LF attack, it has a 3% accuracy loss. Our SkyMask achieves the highest accuracy rate on Fashion-MNIST under different attacks compared to all others. Scaling attack does not show an effective impact on all the defense methods.

The HAR dataset has a real-world data distribution, making the experiment more meaningful and closer to reality. We can see in the HAR part of Table I that Trim, Krum, and their variants cannot work well. FLTrust always has a little gap with the accuracy of models not under attack, which means it could not eliminate the impact of attacks, but it is still acceptable. Unlike all these defense methods, our SkyMask keeps the global model immune to attacks.

As Section IV-A6 describes, the server does not need to consume resources to generate a root model if the fraction of malicious clients is less than 50%. In the 20% case, as shown in Table I, SkyMask-NR achieves good results under any attack and on any dataset, which shows the same defensive capability as SkyMask. Therefore, if the server confirms that the number of malicious clients is less than half the total number, it can choose SkyMask-NR as the defense strategy to reduce the overhead while maintaining the same defensive capability. For generalization, SkyMask can be applied to handle more cases.

In Table I, almost all other robust aggregation algorithms affect the convergence prediction accuracy in the no-attack case. For instance, FLTrust has an accuracy loss of about 2% for the non-IID case on CIFAR-10 dataset, and Krum algorithm has an accuracy loss ranging from about 4% to 20% on different datasets.

In the Fashion-MNIST part of Table II, we can see that it is hard for Tolpegin defense to detect malicious clients stably, especially under Fang-Krum attack and Min-Sum attack. Its FPR and FNR are pretty high, so it fails to defend against attacks effectively and loses a lot of benign information. Quite the opposite, SkyMask perfectly completes the detection task and achieves an FNR of less than 4‰  on Fashion-MNIST dataset with a CNN model, which means that the server hardly misses any malicious client, and it can eliminate the harm of attacks. SkyMask also achieves an FPR of less than 3‰ , so it can preserve most benign clients and better characterize the global data distribution.

In the CIFAR-10 part of Table II, Tolpegin defense performs even worse in the non-IID case with large model architecture (ResNet20). Except for Fang-Trim attack, all other attacks greatly harm it. The large FNR of Tolpegin defense means many malicious clients complete their attacks. The large FPR of Tolpegin defense shows that the remaining benign clients may lose some representation, so Tolpegin defense achieves a lousy performance. In the IID case, Tolpegin defense resumes partial defensive capability, but there is still about 10% FNR under Fang-Krum attack. However, our SkyMask achieves the same prediction accuracy as a no-attack case, with FPR less than 5% and FNR less than 3%.

Table IV shows that SkyMask can work well even if the number of clients increases to 1000 on Fashion-MNIST.
As the number of clients increases, more malicious clients are missed under Min-Sum and Fang-Krum attack, but the FNR is still lower than 1.6%. In addition, the missed malicious local models do not affect the performance of the global model. We can see that the global model of SkyMask achieves the same testing accuracy as the unattacked global model’s obtained by FedAvg.
